"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446333","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer on this subject given to him by the Prime Minister on 25 January 2016, UIN 23433.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-28T14:58:43.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446333/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446333/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will disclose a summary of his Department's legal advice to the (a) Joint Committee on Human Rights and (b) Intelligence and Security Committee relevant to the drone strike that killed Reyaad Khan on 21 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","23431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446334","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>Our Embassy in Tel Aviv is in regular contact with representatives of churches on a range of issues, including to discuss concern about attacks on places of worship. The last attack occurred on 17 January 2016 where the Dormition Abbey compound of the Orthodox Church in the Old City of Jerusalem was vandalised with anti-Christian slogans. The ‘Tag Meir’ organisation has listed 44 cases of vandalism and arson on Christian and Muslim places of worship in Israel and the West Bank since December 2009.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-28T15:00:44.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446334/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446334/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Israel: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the UK Embassy in Israel has taken to monitor attacks on Christian places of worship.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","23464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446335","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>The UK and the four other Non-Proliferation Treaty Nuclear Weapons States voted against the Resolution “Taking forward multilateral nuclear disarmament negotiations” in the UN General Assembly First Committee which established an Open Ended Working Group. The Government believes that productive results can only be ensured through a consensus-based approach that takes into account the wider global security environment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-28T14:56:48.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446335/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446335/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Nuclear Disarmament","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proposal the Government plans to put to the second UN open-ended working group on nuclear disarmament.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","23329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446336","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>Governance of Bahrain is a matter for all political parties in Bahrain. That is why we encourage all political parties, including Al Wefaq who boycotted elections in November 2014, to engage constructively in political dialogue in order to reach an inclusive political settlement. 14 out of 40 MPs are independent Shia who chose to stand and were elected in 2014 elections. 3 of these are women.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-25T16:45:47.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446336/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446336/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Bahrain: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether the Shia in Bahrain accept the Al Khalifa government as the legitimate government of that country.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","23382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446337","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain - including at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting which was most recently held in November 2015. If we have specific concerns around convictions or sentencing, we raise these with the Government of Bahrain as part of our wider dialogue on human rights and reform.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-25T16:50:09.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446337/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446337/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the number of political prisoners in Bahrain; and if he will make representations to the government of Bahrain calling for the release of such prisoners.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","23381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446338","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>Our records show 57 breaches by commercial third party suppliers in handling secure materials for the years in question. This is broken down by year as follows:</p><p>2014/15 - 47</p><p>2015/16 - 10</p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has rigorous formal procedures for reporting, investigating and monitoring any incidents involving the loss or compromise of sensitive data for which it is responsible. Our policies and procedures are designed to ensure that we are compliant with the Data Protection Act 1998 and HMG’s Security Policy Framework. Responsibility for this compliance is shared with Suppliers through appropriate contract terms and conditions.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-28T15:18:41.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446338/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446338/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, on how many occasions his Department has been notified by external consultants or other third parties of breaches by employees or subcontractors of those consultants of document retention or security policies relating to confidential or secure materials in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","23481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446339","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, my hon Friend the Member for Penrith and The Border (Mr Stewart) on 22 January to question number 23306.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-01-28T14:54:35.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446339/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446339/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade: Hanoi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which Ministers and staff of his Department will be attending the Hanoi Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade in November 2016; and what the projected cost of that attendance will be in (a) staff salaries, (b) travel and (c) other costs.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","23305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446340","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>The UK has consistently called on all parties to clarify the legal basis for their claims in the South China Sea. We continue to urge all parties to pursue their claims peacefully in accordance with international law, in particular the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), raised the situation in the South China Sea with China during his recent visit to Beijing on 5 January.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-01-28T16:37:01.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446340/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446340/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","South China Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made a formal request for the Government of the People's Republic of China to state the legal basis for its territorial claims in the South China Sea.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","23312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446341","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>We recognise the situation is desperate for many communities within Syria and Iraq. We condemn in the strongest terms the atrocities committed by Daesh against all civilians, including Christians and other minorities, as well as the majority Muslim population in Syria and Iraq.</p><p>The International Syria Support Group (ISSG) has agreed that protecting the rights of all Syrians, regardless of ethnicity or religious denomination is fundamental. This means that Syrian minorities will be included as the political process progresses. Through our membership of the ISSG, we will ensure that this is adhered to.</p><p>The Global Coalition has provided air support to the Syrian Democratic Forces (which include Syrian Christian members) in their fight against Daesh.</p><p>Ultimately, the best way of safeguarding minority rights is by defeating Daesh and establishing peace and stability in the region. The UK has been at the forefront of these efforts and, together with our allies, has a comprehensive strategy to deal with Daesh.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-27T15:07:00.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446341/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446341/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-20","Syria: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to protect Christians in Syria from persecution by Daesh.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","23250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446342","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>Public Health England part funded the PROUD study that examined the effectiveness of pre-exposure prophylaxis in preventing HIV infection in men who have sex with men. The results of the study were published in September 2015.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-28T11:35:30.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446342/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446342/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","HIV Infection: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research his Department has conducted or commissioned on the effectiveness of pre-exposure prophylaxis in preventing HIV infection in men who have sex with men.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","23245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446343","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>Funding announced by the Prime Minister on 11 January 2016 for mental health crisis response and home treatment teams will be allocated through clinical commissioning group baseline funding. The allocations will be in line with the net cost agreed as part of the spending review process.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-25T16:29:56.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446343/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446343/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 11 January 2016, on life chances, how the £400 million funding for community and home mental health teams will be allocated.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","23473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446344","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Life Chances Fund is an £80m outcomes fund that will focus upon supporting the creation of locally developed social impact bonds tackling a range of social problems. In his speech, the Prime Minister announced that up to £30m of the Life Chances Fund would be made available to support drug and alcohol rehabilitation. The detailed criteria for the fund, including timescales, is being developed but it will provide a portion of outcome payments for locally commissioned social impact bonds where some of the benefits and savings generated fall to central government.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-25T15:18:58.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446344/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446344/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-20","Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 11 January 2016, on life chances, what period the £30 million social investment outcomes fund will cover; when that funding will become available; and to which bodies that funding will be made available.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","23474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446345","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Early Intervention Psychosis access standard will be monitored via the new Mental Health Service Dataset which is managed and reported against by the Health and Social Care Information Centre.</p><br /><p>As this is a new collection, reporting will be phased starting with basic counts in March 2016 and building in detail as quality is assured. In the meantime NHS England has implemented a bespoke collection to monitor progress against the referral to treatment element of the standard, the first report of which is likely to be available in March 2016.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-25T16:27:43.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446345/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446345/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 11 January 2016, on life chances, how the waiting time target for patients with psychosis will be monitored; and when the first results of that monitoring will be published.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","23475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446346","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>In vitro fertilisation treatment is provided in all four NHS England Regions. The level of provision of infertility treatment, as for all health services they commission, is decided by local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and will take into account the needs of the population overall. The CCG’s decisions are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs. As such, provision of services will vary in response to local needs.</p><br /><p>NHS England expects that all those involved in commissioning infertility treatment services to be fully aware of the importance of having regard to the National Institute for Health and Care fertility guidelines.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-25T17:02:03.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446346/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446346/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, in which regions the NHS provides funding for IVF treatment.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","23477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446347","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Department’s Security and Business Continuity team does not collect this information centrally and therefore does not hold this information.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>The Department includes terms and conditions in its contracts that require suppliers to inform us of any such breaches that may have taken place. Any occurrences would have to be reported directly to all local contract owners and to identify these would require trawling across all the Department’s branches that would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-28T11:13:26.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446347/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446347/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Department of Health: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on how many occasions his Department has been notified by external consultants or other third parties of breaches by employees or subcontractors of those consultants of document retention or security policies relating to confidential or secure materials in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","23482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446348","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-28T12:04:42.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446348/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446348/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Accident and Emergency Departments: Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many admissions there were to accident and emergency departments of children requiring tooth extraction in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","23363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446349","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>A recent search of the National Reporting Learning System was carried out of all medication incidents reported as occurring between the dates 1 October 2014 and 31 December 2015.</p><br /><p>This search used key word searches most likely to identify the requested incidents. The search mechanism available does not allow us to confirm that the patients involved with these incidents have Parkinson’s disease but it was focused on medication incidents involving drugs commonly used in Parkinson’s. It is possible that there are additional relevant incidents.</p><br /><p>The information requested is provided in the attached table.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-25T16:54:37.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446349/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446349/answer","PQ23406 Table.doc","PQ23406 Table.doc","Medication incidents and Parkinson's disease","Medication incidents and Parkinson's disease","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446349/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many incidents of medication errors involving hospital patients with Parkinson's disease resulting in (a) no, (b) low, (c) moderate and (d) severe harm were reported to the National Reporting and Learning System in the last quarter of 2014 and in each quarter of 2015; and which reporting organisation reported each such incident.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","23406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446350","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Department works with charities and other voluntary sector organisations and makes grant and procurement payments to these organisations. In 2014-15, £120 million was paid to the voluntary sector. Payment data is held at voluntary sector level, as such, charities are not separately categorised within this data set. It would incur disproportionate cost to extract this subset of the information.</p><br /><p>Payments made through the procurement route are processed in line with Departmental processes, which are consistent with payments made to other organisations. Grant payments are made in accordance with the individual terms of the grant.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-25T16:25:03.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446350/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446350/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Department of Health: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department paid to charities in 2014-15; and what criteria were used to make decisions about those payments.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446351","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Sexual Health and HIV Forum met 15 times between March 2011 and March 2015. The Forum was discontinued in September 2015. Details of dates of meetings and those who attended are shown in the attached document.</p><br /><p>Public Health England is considering how to take forward appropriate stakeholder relationships in the future.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-25T16:45:38.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446351/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446351/answer","PQ23396 Document.pdf","PQ23396 Document.pdf","Sexual Health Forum Meetings March 2011/March 2015","Sexual Health Forum Meetings March 2011/March 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446351/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Sexual Health Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many times the Sexual Health Forum has met in each of the last five years; what the dates were of each such meeting; and who attended each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","23396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446352","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>The following table shows the number of pre-registration nurse training places that were available for each year since 2009.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Nursing</p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Planned</p></td><td><p>21,337</p></td><td><p>20,327</p></td><td><p>18,069</p></td><td><p>17,546</p></td><td><p>18,056</p></td><td><p>19,206</p></td><td><p>20,033</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p><em>Source:</em> multi professional education and training budget monitoring returns</p><br /> <br /><p>Health Education England will formally publish the 2016/17 National Workforce Plan for England in February 2016, this document will include confirmation of the proposed increase in nursing commissions.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-25T13:59:52.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446352/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446352/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many nurse training places were available in England in each year from 2009 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","23380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446353","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Department plans to issue a public consultation around the end of February 2016. An Equality Impact Assessment will be published alongside the consultation document.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-25T14:06:22.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446353/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446353/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the removal of bursaries for nurse training on the diversity of the workforce; and if he will place in the Library a copy of the evidence used in making that assessment.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","23379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446354","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>Data on the number of da Vinci systems for treating prostate cancer, in operation across the National Health Service in England, is not routinely collected or held centrally.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-25T14:03:37.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446354/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446354/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Prostate Cancer: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many da Vinci surgical systems for use in the treatment of prostate cancer are in operation in the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","23429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446355","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>Individual healthcare providers are responsible for ensuring that they have the right level of staffing to provide high quality care to their patients, including embryology services.</p><br /><p>Health Education England (HEE) was established in 2012 to ensure the National Health Service has access to the right numbers of staff, at the right time and with the right skills. In doing so, HEE works with key external stakeholders to develop its National Workforce Plan for England which sets out the number of training places it will commission in the year ahead to meet future local need.</p><br /><p>HEE will continue to work with its 13 Local Education and Training Boards and others to ensure that there are sufficient healthcare scientists, including embryologists, being trained to meet the future needs of patients.</p><br /><p>Currently HEE has 28 reproductive scientists in training (which includes embryology) and are planning a further 11 to start in 2016/17. It takes three years to train a reproductive scientist.</p><br /><p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority have advised that it is not aware of any issues concerning the availability of embryologists in the United Kingdom.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","23391","2016-01-25T16:41:46.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446355/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446355/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Embryology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve recruitment and retention of embryologists in the NHS in (a) England and (b) the North East.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","23390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446356","Department of Health","false","2016-01-25","<p>Individual healthcare providers are responsible for ensuring that they have the right level of staffing to provide high quality care to their patients, including embryology services.</p><br /><p>Health Education England (HEE) was established in 2012 to ensure the National Health Service has access to the right numbers of staff, at the right time and with the right skills. In doing so, HEE works with key external stakeholders to develop its National Workforce Plan for England which sets out the number of training places it will commission in the year ahead to meet future local need.</p><br /><p>HEE will continue to work with its 13 Local Education and Training Boards and others to ensure that there are sufficient healthcare scientists, including embryologists, being trained to meet the future needs of patients.</p><br /><p>Currently HEE has 28 reproductive scientists in training (which includes embryology) and are planning a further 11 to start in 2016/17. It takes three years to train a reproductive scientist.</p><br /><p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority have advised that it is not aware of any issues concerning the availability of embryologists in the United Kingdom.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","23390","2016-01-25T16:41:46.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446356/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446356/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Embryology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of difficulties in recruiting embryologists in (a) England and (b) the North East.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","23391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446357","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>In November 2015, the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the expert body that advises the Government on all immunisation matters, advised that a targeted human papilloma virus vaccination programme should be undertaken for men who have sex with men up to 45 years of age who attend genitourinary medicine and HIV clinics. They noted that this should be subject to procurement of the vaccine and delivery of the programme at a cost-effective price.</p><br /><p>The Department is considering the JCVI’s advice and will confirm its plans in due course.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","23467","2016-01-28T11:33:16.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446357/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446357/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that the men who have sex with men population is aware of the availability of the HPV vaccination at sexual health clinics.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","23466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446358","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>In November 2015, the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the expert body that advises the Government on all immunisation matters, advised that a targeted human papilloma virus vaccination programme should be undertaken for men who have sex with men up to 45 years of age who attend genitourinary medicine and HIV clinics. They noted that this should be subject to procurement of the vaccine and delivery of the programme at a cost-effective price.</p><br /><p>The Department is considering the JCVI’s advice and will confirm its plans in due course.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","23466","2016-01-28T11:33:16.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446358/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446358/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when HPV vaccinations are planned to be available at sexual health clinics to men who have sex with men.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","23467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446359","Department of Health","false","2016-01-26","<p>The Government is committed to making improvements in the quality of care people experience at the end of life.</p><br /><p>In 2014, we set out five priorities for care of the dying person which should underpin the care being delivered to all dying people. The priorities for care state that an individual plan of care, which includes food and drink, symptom control and psychological, social and spiritual support, is agreed, co-ordinated and delivered with compassion.</p><br /><p>In December 2015, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence published guidance on the care of dying adults in the last days of life, including guidance on medical nutrition and hydration. Clinicians and commissioners should have regard to this guidance when making decisions about care for people at the end of life.</p><br /><p>The priorities also set out the critical importance of compassion, respect and dignity in delivering care to dying people and the implications, for staff, commissioners and providers, when making decisions about how end of life care services will meet the needs of local people. The new approach to care, based on these fundamental principles, is being used by clinicians across the country.</p><br /><p>In the coming months, we will be setting out the Department’s plans for building on this progress and achieving further quality improvements in end of life care throughout this Parliament.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-26T14:40:07.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446359/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446359/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve end of life care and the account taken of the needs of patients with regard to (a) hydration and (b) respect and dignity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446360","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>Tackling obesity, particularly in children, is one of our major priorities. Progress has been made in recent years, but we know we have much further to go. We will be launching our childhood obesity strategy shortly. It will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese. It will also set out what more can be done by all sides.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-28T11:18:02.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446360/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446360/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to reduce levels of obesity.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446361","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>This information is not collected. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence Clinical Knowledge Summary (CKS) for Bell’s palsy estimates that the annual incidence of the condition in the United Kingdom is one in 5,000 people and that it most commonly occurs in people aged between 15 and 60 years. The CKS, which is an online resource, can be viewed at the following link:</p><br /><p><a href="http://cks.nice.org.uk/bells-palsy#!topicsummary" target="_blank">http://cks.nice.org.uk/bells-palsy#!topicsummary</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-28T11:15:43.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446361/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446361/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Bell's Palsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have been diagnosed with Bell's Palsy in each of the last five years; and how many such people were (a) women and (b) men aged (i) under 18, (ii) between 18 and 45, (iii) between 45 and 65 and (iv) over 65.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446362","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Department’s Tobacco Control team has not held any discussions with the Royal College of Nursing on the connection between passive smoking and the menopause.</p><br /><p>The Department does, however, regularly review the impacts of smoking as part of its tobacco control strategy.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-28T11:07:54.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446362/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446362/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Passive Smoking: Menopause","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Royal College of Nursing on whether there may be a connection between passive smoking and the menopause.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446363","Department of Health","false","2016-01-28","<p>We recognise the potential influence of online platforms, including social media, on both promoting self-harm and supporting people who have or may be at risk of self-harm.</p><br /><p>There is a link between bullying including cyberbullying and self-harm and the Department for Education produced guidance in October 2014, advising schools about preventing bullying. This guidance refers to new powers under the Education Act 2011 for teachers to search pupils, to confiscate IT equipment including mobile phones and to destroy offensive or inappropriate images.</p><br /><p>The Government continues to provide financial support for the <em>Multi-Centre Study of Self-Harm in England</em>, which monitors trends in self-harm and recognises the potential influence of online platforms on self-harming in young people.</p><br /><p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport expects social media companies to have robust processes in place to address inappropriate and abusive content on their sites. This includes having clear reporting channels, acting promptly to assess reports, and removing content which does not comply with their acceptable use policies or terms and conditions. Social media can also help signpost vulnerable users to helpful sources of information and support.</p><br /><p>Recently, Ofcom led a social media working group on behalf of UK Council for Child Internet Safety to develop best practice guidance to encourage responsible practice from industry, and ensure children using their services are able to do so in a safe and protected way. This guidance was delivered on 22 December 2015 and can be found at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/uk-council-for-child-internet-safety-ukccis" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/uk-council-for-child-internet-safety-ukccis</a></p><br /><p>The Department of Health’s National Institute for Health Research has also funded ongoing research by the Samaritans and Bristol University into the influence on online platforms on suicidal behaviour.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-28T17:44:11.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446363/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446363/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-20","Social Media: Self-harm","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the potential link between social media and self-harm among young people.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446364","Home Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>Tackling domestic violence is a key priority for this Government. We put Domestic Homicide Reviews on a statutory footing in 2011 so that local areas and agencies identify lessons learned to help to prevent future homicides and violence. We have commenced a new domestic abuse offence to tackle controlling and coercive behaviour, and have rolled out Domestic Violence Protection Orders and the Domestic Violence Disclosure Scheme across the country. We have already committed £40 million between 2016 and 2020 to support domestic abuse victims, and provided £2 million to Safelives and Women’s Aid to support early intervention. We will shortly publish a refreshed cross-Government Violence Against Women and Girls strategy setting out how we will do more still to secure long-term funding for domestic violence services and support for all victims.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-25T17:19:07.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446364/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446364/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Domestic Abuse: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the number of women murdered as a result of domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","23493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446365","Home Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>Home Office officials are working closely with our housing providers to ensure that asylum seeker accommodation is not easily identifiable. I am not aware of a uniform door colour being the practice in any other region. My officials have also spoken to our housing providers to tell them that such a practice is not acceptable.</p><p>I was first made aware of this issue when The Times contacted the Home Office in mid-January. G4S has investigated correspondence and discussions on the issue of external door colour in the North East and has confirmed that it was raised in 2012 by a Middlesbrough local councillor and was considered by the G4S audit and assurance team, no complaints from asylum seekers relating to this matter were found and a response was issued.</p><p>As I said to the House on 20 January, I instructed officials to look into this issue as a matter of urgency and I expect that the audit will be concluded on the Home Office side very shortly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","23355 ; 23356 ; 23357","2016-02-02T14:57:41.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446365/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446365/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take steps to ensure that asylum seekers are not housed in properties that make their status as asylum seekers easily identifiable.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","23358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446366","Home Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>There are various requirements for a person to provide their name and address to reveal their identity to the police.</p><p>These include:</p><p>- the Road Traffic Act (RTA) 1988, for example, Section 164 gives constables the power to require the production of a driving license; and Section 165 RTA 1988 gives constables the power to obtain names and addresses of drivers and others, and to require production of evidence of insurance or security and test certificates. Full details of the Act can be seen here: http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1988/52/contents</p><p>- the Police Reform Act, which also gives powers to Police Community Support Officers to require the provision of a name and address in certain circumstances. Full details of the Act can be seen here: http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2002/30/schedule/4/paragraph/1A -</p><p>- the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 which can require a person to reveal their identity in certain circumstances in connection to suspecting them of a specific offence and arrest. Full details of the Act can be seen here: http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1984/60/contents</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-26T16:17:33.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446366/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446366/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Police: Powers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what requirement there is for a person to reveal their identity when requested to do so by a police officer.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","23441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446367","Home Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>Home Office officials are working closely with our housing providers to ensure that asylum seeker accommodation is not easily identifiable. I am not aware of a uniform door colour being the practice in any other region. My officials have also spoken to our housing providers to tell them that such a practice is not acceptable.</p><p>I was first made aware of this issue when The Times contacted the Home Office in mid-January. G4S has investigated correspondence and discussions on the issue of external door colour in the North East and has confirmed that it was raised in 2012 by a Middlesbrough local councillor and was considered by the G4S audit and assurance team, no complaints from asylum seekers relating to this matter were found and a response was issued.</p><p>As I said to the House on 20 January, I instructed officials to look into this issue as a matter of urgency and I expect that the audit will be concluded on the Home Office side very shortly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","23355 ; 23357 ; 23358","2016-02-02T14:57:41.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446367/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446367/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when (a) her Department and (b) the contractor G4S became aware of concerns that asylum seekers were being housed in properties with doors that are all uniform or nearly uniform in colour.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","23356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446368","Home Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>Home Office officials are working closely with our housing providers to ensure that asylum seeker accommodation is not easily identifiable. I am not aware of a uniform door colour being the practice in any other region. My officials have also spoken to our housing providers to tell them that such a practice is not acceptable.</p><p>I was first made aware of this issue when The Times contacted the Home Office in mid-January. G4S has investigated correspondence and discussions on the issue of external door colour in the North East and has confirmed that it was raised in 2012 by a Middlesbrough local councillor and was considered by the G4S audit and assurance team, no complaints from asylum seekers relating to this matter were found and a response was issued.</p><p>As I said to the House on 20 January, I instructed officials to look into this issue as a matter of urgency and I expect that the audit will be concluded on the Home Office side very shortly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","23355 ; 23356 ; 23358","2016-02-02T14:57:41.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446368/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446368/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she expects the inquiry announced by her Department on 20 January 2016 into the housing of asylum seekers in the north-east of England to report its findings.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","23357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446369","Home Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>In respect of the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme we are working with Northern Ireland as well as with other devolved administrations and local authorities to ensure that they are only asked to welcome Syrian refugees that their local structures are able to support. We are talking to them and other partners to ensure that capacity can be identified and the impact on those taking new cases can be managed in a fair and controlled way.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-27T15:43:47.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446369/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446369/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take steps to increase the number of psychological and psychiatric specialist services available for Syrian refugees and asylum seekers in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","23333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446370","Home Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme prioritises those who cannot be supported effectively in their region of origin. Northern Ireland, in common with other devolved administrations and local authorities, is provided with full case details of all referrals before deciding whether to accept them for resettlement so they can make an assessment of whether they have the infrastructure and support networks needed to ensure the appropriate care and integration of these refugees. Whilst the Government provides funding to ensure these needs can be met, it is up to individual local authorities to decide how this should be achieved.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-27T15:46:58.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446370/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446370/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Syrian refugees and asylum seekers were informed of mental health provisions they could expect in Northern Ireland before they agreed to settle there.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","23332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446371","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The information is not readily available and could not be obtained within the proportionate cost limit.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-22T15:13:32.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446371/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446371/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446371/answer/previousversion/40794","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2016 to Question 21728, how many applications for a Tier 2 (General) restricted Certificate of Sponsorship have been rejected on the grounds that the job is in an establishment which provides a take-away service in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","23423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446372","Home Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold the data requested.</p><p>The Home Office collects data from police forces on the number of offences that resulted in a charge but does not collect data on the number of interviews held under caution.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-25T17:26:19.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446372/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446372/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446372/answer/previousversion/40805","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of people who were interviewed under caution (a) for all offences and (b) for sexual offences were subsequently charged in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","23368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446373","Home Office","false","2016-03-17","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the response I gave on 17 March 2016.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-17T12:06:28.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446373/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446373/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446373/answer/previousversion/40818","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20287, when she plans to give a substantive answer to that question.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","23422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446374","Home Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS).</p><p>The 999/112 Liaison Committee, chaired by DCMS, provides a forum for representatives from Government; Communications Providers, including BT (which provides the 999 call handling agency) and Mobile Network Operators (MNOs); emergency services and Ofcom, to discuss 999 operational matters The LC’s main concern is the effective handling and transfer of emergency calls from the public, through call handling agents ,to emergency authorities.</p><p>The “Code of Practice for the Public Emergency Call Service (PECS) between Communications Providers, Call Handing Agencies and the Emergency Authorities” sets out protocols governing 999 calls. This includes guidelines for the Emergency Authorities to manage any occasional situation in which an emergency 999 call is misdirected.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","23401 ; 23404","2016-02-08T15:45:26.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446374/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446374/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446374/answer/previousversion/40798","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Police: Emergency Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department provides to police forces on how to deal with a situation in which an emergency 999 call is erroneously directed to the wrong police force; and what procedures police forces have put in place to deal with such a situation.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446375","Home Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS).</p><p>The 999/112 Liaison Committee, chaired by DCMS, provides a forum for representatives from Government; Communications Providers, including BT (which provides the 999 call handling agency) and Mobile Network Operators (MNOs); emergency services and Ofcom, to discuss 999 operational matters The LC’s main concern is the effective handling and transfer of emergency calls from the public, through call handling agents ,to emergency authorities.</p><p>The “Code of Practice for the Public Emergency Call Service (PECS) between Communications Providers, Call Handing Agencies and the Emergency Authorities” sets out protocols governing 999 calls. This includes guidelines for the Emergency Authorities to manage any occasional situation in which an emergency 999 call is misdirected.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","23400 ; 23404","2016-02-08T15:45:26.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446375/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446375/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446375/answer/previousversion/40800","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Police: Emergency Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether (a) Ministers and (b) officials in her Department have met (i) mobile telephone operators and (ii) BT to discuss the transfer of emergency calls made from mobile telephones to the wrong police force.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446376","Home Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS).</p><p>The 999/112 Liaison Committee, chaired by DCMS, provides a forum for representatives from Government; Communications Providers, including BT (which provides the 999 call handling agency) and Mobile Network Operators (MNOs); emergency services and Ofcom, to discuss 999 operational matters The LC’s main concern is the effective handling and transfer of emergency calls from the public, through call handling agents ,to emergency authorities.</p><p>The “Code of Practice for the Public Emergency Call Service (PECS) between Communications Providers, Call Handing Agencies and the Emergency Authorities” sets out protocols governing 999 calls. This includes guidelines for the Emergency Authorities to manage any occasional situation in which an emergency 999 call is misdirected.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","23400 ; 23401","2016-02-08T15:45:26.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446376/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446376/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446376/answer/previousversion/40804","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Police: Emergency Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that people using mobile telephones to call 999 are put in touch with the correct police force; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446377","Home Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>We are clear that all crimes reported to the police should be taken seriously, but it is an operational decision for the police to decide how best to respond to an individual report of crime including where a criminal act may be in progress.</p><p>While we do expect the nature of the police response to take account of the relevant circumstances, including any vulnerabilities or aggravating factors such as where members of the public may be at risk of harm, the Home Office does not issue guidance to the police on such operational matters.</p><p>These are the responsibility of Chief Constables, in association with Police and Crime Commissioners, and guidance may be published by the independent College of Policing.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-25T18:58:24.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446377/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446377/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446377/answer/previousversion/40801","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Police: Emergency Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has issued to police forces on their emergency response to incidents reporting breaking and entering, burglary and vandalism to vehicles, and other criminal activity when the criminal act is reported as being in progress.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446378","Home Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Home Office has no recorded breaches of material classified as ‘confidential’ or ‘official sensitive’ or above for contractors during the period from January 2014 to date. During this period, in April 2014, the Government Security Classification markings changed from a six-tier protective marking system (unclassified, protect, restricted, confidential, secret and top secret) to a three-tier system (official, secret and top secret). Official - Sensitive is a handling caveat of the 'Official' tier in the Government Security Classifications (GSC) Policy. Official-Sensitive is not a separate classification.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-27T16:10:22.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446378/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Home Office: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions her Department has been notified by external consultants or other third parties of breaches by employees or subcontractors of those consultants of document retention or security policies relating to confidential or secure materials in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","23483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446379","Home Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>Home Office officials are working closely with our housing providers to ensure that asylum seeker accommodation is not easily identifiable. I am not aware of a uniform door colour being the practice in any other region. My officials have also spoken to our housing providers to tell them that such a practice is not acceptable.</p><p>I was first made aware of this issue when The Times contacted the Home Office in mid-January. G4S has investigated correspondence and discussions on the issue of external door colour in the North East and has confirmed that it was raised in 2012 by a Middlesbrough local councillor and was considered by the G4S audit and assurance team, no complaints from asylum seekers relating to this matter were found and a response was issued.</p><p>As I said to the House on 20 January, I instructed officials to look into this issue as a matter of urgency and I expect that the audit will be concluded on the Home Office side very shortly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","23356 ; 23357 ; 23358","2016-02-02T14:57:41.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446379/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446379/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether contractors have housed asylum seekers in properties with doors that are all uniform or nearly uniform in colour in regions other than the North East.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","23355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446380","Home Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>In order for the Dublin Regulation to apply an application for international protection must be lodged in one of the participating States.</p><p>A person who has arrived in the UK clandestinely from France who then claims asylum in the UK can be returned to France under the terms of the Dublin Regulation even if they have not claimed asylum in France as long as the criteria in the Regulation demonstrate that France is the responsible state. For example, asylum seekers can be returned if they have close family members in France, a visa or residence permit has been issued to them by the French authorities or if they have been in France illegally for a period of 5 months or more.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-25T17:10:51.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446380/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446380/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 19 January 2016 to Questions 22594 and 22595, whether it is her Department's policy that an applicant for international protection who enters the UK from France clandestinely but had not made an application for international protection in France should be returned to France in accordance with the Dublin Regulation.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","23455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446381","Home Office","false","2016-01-29","<p>The UK remains committed to its global leadership role in helping to tackle the illegal wildlife trade. During his visit to Vietnam in July 2015, the Prime Minister confirmed that the UK would provide £200,000 to support Vietnam in hosting a third high level international conference on the illegal wildlife trade. The Conference, to be held on 24-25 November 2016, will build on the successful London and Kasane Conferences of 2014 and 2015. Decisions about who will represent the UK at the Vietnam Conference have not yet been made.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-29T14:32:06.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446381/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446381/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade: Hanoi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which Ministers and staff of her Department will be attending the Hanoi Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade in November 2016; and what the projected cost of that attendance will be in (a) staff salaries, (b) travel and (c) other costs.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","23304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446382","Home Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Immigration Health Surcharge was introduced in April last year to ensure that temporary, non-EEA migrants (unless subject to an exemption), who apply to come to the UK to work, study or join family, for a time-limited period of more than 6 months or who make an application to remain in the UK, contribute to the extensive and high quality range of NHS services available to them in a manner in line with their immigration status. This includes individuals resident in the UK with temporary spousal visas of more than 6 months, until such time they are eligible for indefinite leave to remain in which case the Immigration Health Surcharge does not apply.</p><p>It gives migrant’s access to the NHS on the same terms as a permanent UK resident. The surcharge is set at a competitive rate and is a lower cost over the period of stay than the cost of even basic private medical insurance. In setting the Immigration Health Surcharge level at £200 per annum per migrant and £150 for students, the last Government considered the range of health services available without charge to migrants, the valuable contribution migrants make to our country and the need to ensure that the UK remains an attractive destination for global talent.</p><p>In the first 6 months since its introduction, the Immigration Health Surcharge collected more than £100 million in income for the NHS.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-28T16:08:54.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446382/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446382/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the rationale is for people on spousal visas resident in the UK being required to pay a health surcharge as part of their visa.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","23278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446383","Home Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>Government estimates on the number of illegal migrants currently living in the UK by constituent region and nation are not available.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-28T15:41:36.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446383/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446383/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446383/answer/previousversion/40819","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Undocumented Migrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of illegal immigrants in residence in each constituent region and nation of the UK in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","23254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446385","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-27","<p>DFID is not aware of any notifications from external consultants, or other third parties, of breaches to its Information Security Management Controls in the past two years.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-27T15:33:43.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446385/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446385/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-20","Department for International Development: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, on how many occasions her Department has been notified by external consultants or other third parties of breaches by employees or subcontractors of those consultants of document retention or security policies relating to confidential or secure materials in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","23484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446386","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-27","<p>The UK is a top three donor to polio eradication, with a £300 million commitment over six years from 2013/14 to 2018/19. Of this, £100 million was disbursed in the financial year of 2013/2014, £50 million in 2014/15, and £65 million in 2015/16. The UK will provide £39 million in 2016/17, £29 million in 2017/18 and £17 million in 2018/19.</p><p>UK support has been critical in bringing us one step closer to the finish line of a world free from polio, something people across the country can be immensely proud of.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-01-27T15:32:20.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446386/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446386/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-20","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 6 January 2016 to Question 20675, how much of the £300 million provided to eradicate polio was spent in each of the last three years; and how much will be spent in each of the next four years.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","23362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446387","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-27","<p>The UK supports the G7 Climate Risk Insurance Initiative and is committed to contributing to meeting the collective target set out in the Elmau declaration of helping up to an additional 400 million people in the most vulnerable developing countries to gain access to climate risk insurance by 2020. UK support under the Initiative includes a commitment of up to £100m to African Risk Capacity (ARC) and £15m for the Pacific Catastrophe Risk Assessment and Financing Initiative. Of this, the UK has contributed £32m so far to ARC.</p><p>On scaling up support to weather indexed microinsurance, the UK currently provides some support to livestock insurance in Kenya to improve the product offered to pastoralists and increase the role of the private sector. The UK also provides index-based insurance through the CGIAR climate change, agriculture and food security research programme (CGIAR-CCAFS). In September 2015, the Prime Minister announced that the UK would provide at least £5.8 billion of climate finance over the next five years. This is likely to include further support for climate risk insurance.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-01-27T15:36:03.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446387/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446387/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-20","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to InsuResilience, the G7 Initiative on Climate Risk Insurance, if she will make it her policy to (a) allocate additional funding of £100 million to that programme, (b) scale up by at least £50 million weather-indexed microinsurance that provides direct coverage for smallholder farmers pastoralists and other vulnerable groups and (c) increase her Department's grant funding for the African Risk Capacity to £20 million in order to improve the capacity of that programme to meet its targets.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","23366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446388","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-25","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-25T15:37:46.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446388/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446388/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-20","Youth Custody: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff working in (a) young offender institutions, (b) secure training centres and (c) secure children's homes have been (i) suspended following a child protection allegation (ii) disciplined following a child protection allegation, (iii) dismissed following a child protection allegation and (iv) convicted of sexual or violent offences against children in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","23395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446389","Home Office","false","2016-01-25","<p>The available information on the number of convictions for homicide offences in England and Wales is given in the table and is taken from the Home Office Homicide Index.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><strong>Table 1: Offenders convicted of homicide<sup>1,2,3</sup>, 2010/11 to 2013/14</strong></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>England and Wales</strong></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td><strong></strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Outcome<sup>4</sup></strong></td><td><strong>2010/11</strong></td><td><strong>2011/12</strong></td><td><strong>2012/13</strong></td><td><strong>2013/14</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong></strong></td><td colspan="4"><em>Numbers</em></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Convicted of homicide:</strong></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Murder</td><td>259</td><td>236</td><td>243</td><td>194</td></tr><tr><td>Sec. 2 manslaughter</td><td>26</td><td>26</td><td>25</td><td>16</td></tr><tr><td>Other manslaughter</td><td>133</td><td>98</td><td>110</td><td>93</td></tr><tr><td>Infanticide</td><td>2</td><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total convicted of homicide</strong></td><td><strong>420</strong></td><td><strong>361</strong></td><td><strong>379</strong></td><td><strong>306</strong></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Number of homicide cases completed at court <sup>5</sup></strong></td><td><strong>357</strong></td><td><strong>326</strong></td><td><strong>326</strong></td><td><strong>239</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong></strong></td><td><strong></strong></td><td><strong></strong></td><td><strong></strong></td><td><strong></strong></td></tr><tr><td><em>1. Source: Homicide Index, Home Office </em></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5">2. Homicide Index data are not designated as National Statistics</td></tr><tr><td colspan="5">3. As at 5 November 2014; figures are subject to revision as cases are dealt with by the police and the courts, or as further information becomes available.</td></tr><tr><td colspan="4">4. Includes offenders whose court proceedings were completed by 5 November 2014.</td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5">5. These figures are based on number of homicide cases concluded at court (e.g. the number of victims in currently recorded homicides), rather than the number of suspects who have been to court.</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Data are based on the number of offenders whose court proceedings have been completed. Due to the time it can take for cases to pass through the criminal justice system, more recent years will contain a greater number of homicides that remain under investigation and therefore fewer convictions in those years. Updated figures for the number of people convicted of homicide in previous years, along with new figures for 2014/15 will be published by the Office for National Statistics in their Focus on Violence publication on 11 February 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-25T19:05:36.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446389/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446389/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446389/answer/previousversion/40795","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-20","Homicide: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the change was in the number of people convicted of murder between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","23459"
